7.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2548<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/20/02 2:26:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=198.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  The Biggest Nuclear Spacecraft.</span><hr size=1> This is very futuristic and belongs in the realm of Dyson Spheres. Imagine a ship which uses a Star and manipulates it to produce thrust. Yes, it would have to make a Battlestar Galactica look microscopic. Theoretically, could it be done and what kind of thrust could you get out of a G_Type Star? <br>
When the energy is spent, you can just leave the Iron Core behind and take another Star. The best part is it might even be inertialess. If you don't use a chamber. <br>
Crushing acceleration velocities can be used this way. The Sun accelerates and the massive ship tags along under the gravitational pull of the Sun. Freefalling toward the Sun as the Sun flies off towards Alpha Centaurii at hundreds of G's.  I think modern computers could handle the job of balancing the distance of the Sun against it's acceleration. Gentle firings of reaction mass to counter or aid the Suns pull until stability is reached. If it's ever reached. Excess Heat shouldn't be a challenge to control. The Ship is going to be Planetary size. Hopefully massive enough that it doesn't need to get within barbecue distance of the Sun. <br>
<br>
