<br>
 It's called Starlifting, or Stellar Husbandry, first proposed by David Criswell, a well respected physicist. His numbers stand today, and he asserts that it's no radically new technology and completely basic physics. An example of what they call <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.aleph.se/Trans/Tech/Megascale/">Megascale Engineering</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
I mentioned transhumanism in another board here. Here's more of it.<br>
<br>
 The idea is that this may be easier than mining the gas giants for building materials (after we've taken apart all the asteroids, short period comets, and small moons).<br>
 Build big (smallish asteroid mass) stations in a close solar orbit (11 solar radii out from the center). Fire ion, electron, or charged particle beams from one to a collector at the next in the ring -so on, back &amp; forth. Solar powered, eventually re-use power from the beams.<br>
 Conductor in a magnetic field means you can modify that field. (one of the several feasible methods of starlifting).<br>
<br>
Note that this is much more feasible than the Ringworld, since that involves unobtainable materials for the ring floor &quot;scrith&quot; (tensile strength like the strong nuclear force). Starlifting, like space industry, only involves new ways of putting together things we do every day. While we don't know the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>best</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> answer to every technical question, we do know several ways, any of which would work well enough (much like Orion, eh?).<br>
