 We calm down the ecliptic, eliminating deadly solar flares. Induce plasma ejections at the polar regions, where we collect stuff to cool it and store it where it won't boil off. Coronal mass ejections are from solar flares; Earth-ocean masses of stuff, ionized and thrown scattered across the solar system.<br>
 We instead, collect it and use it to build habitats &amp; such (building up the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.student.nada.kth.se/~asa/dysonFAQ.html#WHAT">Dyson Cloud</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> of habitats around the star -note: not the cheesy S.F. solid sphere).<br>
 It could start any time we get large-scale construction in space, and it will take hundreds of thousands of years to see any detectable difference from lifting massive amounts of stuff off the Sun. Within millions of years, we've started lowering the Sun's mass.<br>
 A star of about .75-.83 solar masses is much more stable than ours, and the expected lifespan for a star like this is several tens or hundreds of billions of years -larger stars burn hotter and more fiercely, wasting their fuel.<br>
<br>
Harnessed solar flares can push magsail craft, while not harming anything else.<br>
