Kind of backwards &amp; counter-intuitive, when you look at a star's lifetime.<br>
 Inwards pressure from stuff piled on top drives up the internal temperature, causing it to burn hotter and faster. Reducing the mass reduces this pressure, so it burns slower.<br>
 Effective power output might be somewhat less, but the slightly smaller surface area is radiating this energy, so the effective apparent heat felt from sunlight and the apparent brightness of the Sun is the same (someone better qualified please check me on all this).<br>
 When a star starts to run out of fuel, it goes haywire, and all sorts of processes release energy bloating it out into a giant, hence the uninhabitability of the Earth long before it gets swallowed up, because the larger surface area of the star bakes us.<br>
<br>
